Oct 27 2009 	Au revoir Paris Hotel! We won't miss you much...	My wife and I travelled to Vegas for the first time for a long business weekend and stayed at the Paris hotel for four days. We were originally supposed to stay at the Wynn, but our arrangements were made by corporate folks who probably didn't know the difference between some of the Hotel/Casinos on the strip...big mistake. This hotel, like many others on the strip, has taken its theme of &quot;classical French decor&quot; and turned it into a horrible parody of itself. Everything about this place was gauche.Check in was marred by the fact that no King bed was available, despite a request weeks earlier. An indifferent shoulder shrug was our consolation for this inconvenience. The check in folks were clearly immersed in their roles as annoyed French locals and didn't break character the entire stay. Amazing!The room is on par with the finest 2 star hotels in rural Arkansas....dirty, small, poorly furnished and dim. The beds are an absolute joke with awful linens, mattress that rivals my pullout couch at home, pillows that smelled oddly like eggs. The shower water pressure is like an 80 year male with end stage prostate enlargement. No coffee machines, electronic amenities are circa 1986....old TV kept switching off every 20 minutes for no reason, limited stations, Wifi? Mais non, there is nothing remotely business worthy of a hotel that is supposed to cater to the conventioneer or business person!Room service took over an hour for a simple breakfast order and I think I saw plates lying in the hallway for two days before they were collected off the dingy carpet. Did I mention the carpet looked like floral and paisly threw up on each other? Mmmm, this place just keeps getting more French every minute!The only restaurant we visited was Mon Ami Gabi, which was actually very good! Eat outside on the patio for a great view of the Bellagio, where you will invariably want to stay after this place leaves its stain on you. Otherwise food and drink are predictably overpriced, and the cocktails were incredibly weak....much more so than any other casino we visited. Stick to beer and wine and you'll be fine. I am not much of a gambler, so I can't really comment on the experience...suffice it to say that if you are not a smoker, you will not like walking around this place. Paris is ventilated like hermetically sealed tupperware....even for an occasional smoker like myself, my eyes and lungs burned like a raging UTI all weekend. The only, and I mean ONLY thing this place has going for it is the location. Centrally located along the strip, I spent most of my time in other hotels and casinos that far surpassed the Paris experience. Of course, that would have meant paying a bit more, but this place is an absolute joke. If you have any travel experience whatsoever, you'll know that this is a Howard Johnson with cheap &quot;French-like&quot; amenities, substandard cleanliness and spotty serviceFrom what we saw, I'd really recommend the Venetian, Bellagio, or Wynn. Just stay away from this horrible excuse for the &quot;French experience.&quot; At least in Paris, France, I would overpriced rooms and lousy service....just not in Vegas.	
