Oct 24 2009 	Wouldn't Spend My Own Money here	Just completed a 4-night stay here as part of a convention. Reserved a king non-smoking room. Arrived around 10 p.m. on a Saturday night. Was told they didn't have a King room, but were giving me a non-smoking room. We knew things were not going well as we approached the room. There were holes kicked in the wall in at least three places and the whole floor seemed kind of shabby. The room was non-smoking, but only if you believe that non-smoking means &quot;no one has smoked in this room during the last 20 minutes.&quot; Complained, but was told no other rooms were available.This room was along the lines of a 2.5 star room. Thin towels, older furniture, no coffee maker, smallish. Certainly not worth paying more than $50 per night. There was a refrigerator, but it was stocked with overpriced booze and munchies and set to automatically charge you if you moved anything.After complaining again the next day, we were upgraded to a mini-suite for the remainder of our stay. Better, but still not great. The room was quite large and had a sofa, chair and wet bar with a usable refrigerator. There was a separate corridor leading on one end to a large walk-in closet with a lighted make-up table. At the other end was an oversize bathroom with a separate shower and jaccuzzi bath and a separate toilet room. This time, there was an in-room coffee set-up. The carpeting in the room was tired. This room still had the same thin towels, no bathrobes, and neither room had a 21st century TV.There was some serious nickle-and-diming. Want to use the gym (above average, but nothing great), $25 per person, per day. Want internet access, another $15 daily gouge.Had room service twice. It was overpriced, but decent. Expect 1.5 hour delays on breakfast unless you order the night before. The breakfast buffet downstairs, however, is great value at $15 per head. There is a vast selection, including omelet, crepe and belgian waffle stations. We ate there twice. Ate at the steakhouse. Again, overpriced for what you got. There are far better steakhouses in this town. We also had a meal at the burger-oriented sports bar, which was fairly priced an had great service from happy, friendly servers. One major disappointment was the Louis Cafe, where my wife was ignored for half an hour, which was probably the high point of her dining experience. Thereafter she was treated to shabby service, cold food, and a watery drink. As a tip, she wrote on the check, &quot;AWFUL DINING EXPERIENCE!&quot; Hope they get the message.All-in-all, Paris was a poor choice for a convention hotel. Judging it from the point of view of a casino hotel, it was just OK. From what I have seen, there are far better hotels for the money to be had in Las Vegas. I would not return here on my own dime and would probably stay elsewhere even if a business meeting/convention were venued here.	
