Oct 18 2009 	Nice hotel perfect location on the strip	Stayed here from Sunday - Wednesday. First night rate was $105, last two nights were $60. Breakfast buffet is excellent but the server did not do a great job at checking on us. A small pizzeria had excellent food and was wonderful for a late night snack. The casino is nice and I won $50 on the nickle machine after just two spins. Check-in and check-out were simple. Stayed on the 18th floor and the elevators are quick. The room and bathroom were a nice size. I did notice the outside windows needed cleaning. Coffee in one of the shops was $3.50, but that was expected at a luxuy hotel. The location is perfect because it's right in front of the Bellagio and we watched the water show from our hotel window. Planet Hollywood is on one side and Bally's is on the other.The city bus stops right outside the hotel and the $7 pass to ride all day was perfect for getting around the strip all day. A shuttle near the bell stand takes you to the Rio for free. We got on just to see what was over there and it was okey. On arrival, traffic on the street was awful, causing our taxi fare to be $24. Going back to the airport at mid day, our taxi fare was only $13 for the 10 minute ride. If you want to eat outside the hotel, we found the lunch buffett at Bellagio and Ceasars Palace were the best. MGM's dinner buffett was very disappointing. Pink's hot dog stand is next door in Planet Hollywood and that was decent for dinner one night. Don't buy bottled water if you play the slots...the waitresses will bring it to you while you are seated. Three printers are in the lobby to get your boarding passes. The cost was a $5 minimum to log on to the internet. People were using them like mad to print out Southwest Boarding passes. If you have a blackberry, just log in and check in, you can always get the boarding pass at the airport - especially if you have to stand in line to check your bags anyway! No freebies at this hotel, no bathrobe, slippers, coffee pot, paper, etc. You will pay for everything, but you will have a good time - it's Vegas!	
Oct 18 2009 	I love the Paris	This is the second time I've stayed here. It's a large hotel but has a more intimate feel than some of the other large casino hotels, and a guest is least likely to get lost. Check-in formalities was handled at the Diamond check-in room as I was a conference attendee. The elevators are close to check-in, which is nice. The regular check-in area wasn't too busy early in the morning but developed a queue after 12 pm.The room is comfortable, large and nicely appointed but not luxurious as a 5 star but is a solid 4 star, which is what most publications rate this hotel. The room I stayed in showed a little bit of wear and tear on the lounge chairs and the desk area but overall it was above average. The view from my room was towards the Bally Hotel, so it was nothing to brag about, and the windows were actually quite filthy with dust. It made looking out the window rather painful. The bed was comfortable for me and I had no problems with the bedding or pillows. I thought that the wall between the bedroom and the bathroom should have had a picture or something to break up the starkness of that particular wall. The lighting in the room was adequate for leisure and taking care of business work. The television was the standard issue that one finds in most 3 star properties; a flat screen would have been a nice upgrade to the room. The closet space is contained in the television armoir cabinet. It wasn't my favorite arrangement as I prefer a separate closet, but was efficient I suppose. There was the standard ironing board and iron. There was an in-room refreshment bar if you get the hungries. Also, 24 room service is available. I thought the prices were fair for room service at a Las Vegas hotel. The bathroom was solid 4 star, lined with marble, with a separate bathtub and shower enclosure. What the bathroom could have used was a little more light, especially in the shower enclosure, where it was rather dark and hard to see. Water pressure is very low with a water saver shower head so don't expect taking long, luxurious hot showers; drought plagues much of the US Southwest. A nice bath would probably be the better choice if you have the time to fill up the tub. The bathroom toiletries such as shampoo and conditioner have a very pleasant smell that works well for women but maybe a little to flowerly for men. I found it to be so mild that I doubt it would be an issue for men.The airconditioning system was easy to use and worked well, and was very quiet. The rooms in general were quiet with no noise intrusion from my next door neighbors. Being on a non-smoking floor, I didn't have to worry about obnoxious odors creeping into the room from under the door or the a/c system. I ate at the Eiffel Tower and Le Artiste Steakhouse. Both had very-well prepared foods but the Steakhouse opens up to the casino so smoke was somewhat of an issue for me. The Eiffel Tower Restaurant was excellent, and I would patronize this venue for dinner on my next trip.I love the buffet at the Paris. Granted, it's a hotel buffet so the quality of the food dips a notch below plated service because of the mass quantity preparation and the standtime in the steam trays. Still, the overall quality is very good and the variety of foods from various parts of France make this an adventure for those who like to try something non-conventional versus the typical Las Vegas buffet offerings. The public areas are reminiscent of Paris, which really appeals to me. It may be too &quot;Disneyesque&quot; for many but I think it's well thought out and easy to understand. Most of the hotel casinos in Las Vegas are rather gimmicky anyways. The casino and main walkway through the hotel casino is a little easier to navigate due to one main walkway from the front of the hotel to the back. Walking distances at this hotel are minimal if you want to get down to the action of the first floor or if you're the type to get out of the hotel and explore other places along the Strip. In fact, the central location of the Paris makes it easy to walk most other casino properties in 15 minutes or less. Overall, a nice hotel, not too large, easy to navigate, and intimate enough to where you don't feel like one in a big herd of cattle.	
