Oct 13 2009 	Fairly nice Vegas hotel but low class bedding	I've been to Vegas many times, but this was my first stay at Paris. It's a nice hotel, I'd say it's on par with MGM, but not quite to Bellagio or Venetian standards. My only problem was with the bedding. The mattresses were bouncy and you could practically feel the springs, the sheets were the roughest I've ever had in a nice hotel, and the pillows were lumpy and awful. The feather pillows, you could feel the feathers poking out, so I had housekeeping bring some foam, and they were incredibly lumpy. Very disappointing as the rest of the hotel was fine. The friends I was traveling with mentioned this, as well, and they are not as picky as I am.The room was big, the bathroom was pretty with a separate marble shower. Everything was very clean, and I am a picky traveler. The blow dryer was a &quot;real&quot; dryer, not the usual hotel &quot;breath&quot; dryer. The pool was nice, although too cold to really enjoy in October. I guess it's a seasonal thing, but the pool didn't open until 10a. Even though it was chilly in the mornings, I still would have liked to have my mornings there. There were only a couple of waitpeople working the pool, even though it was a holiday weekend and got pretty crowded in the afternoons.The shops in the hotel are nice, plenty of choices for snacks and dining, and it's small enough to get around easily. The location, in between Ballys and Planet Hollywood, is not great, in my opinion, as neither of those hotels interest me. It's not too hard to get to Bellagio and the Caesar's complex, though.Overall, I would not stay here again simply because of the low grade, motel quality bedding situation. It was not cheap, and for a similar price I think you can do much better in Las Vegas.	
Oct 13 2009 	Great Location food and ambience.	We had a great stay at the Paris Hotel in Vegas. The hotel is beautiful and very well-done, but the best part is its location on the strip. It is very central and you do so much walking in Vegas that this kind of a location is at a premium. Also, the hotel itself is not too big and it is easy to navigate. We used the pool both days and rented a cabana. The pool is large and never seemed the least bit croweded. The cabanas were great, but a bit more expensive than those I've rented at other properties. If you have 6 people or so, then it is totally worth it. I had a massage at the Mandara spa. The therapist was wonderful. DH used the steamroom on the men's side and thoroughly enjoyed it.Overall the service and amenities were great. The staff was friendly and very accomodating. We were in 1034 (premier) and had a great view of the Eiffel tower and some Bellagio fountain views. The sheets on the bed could have used upgrading. They just weren't smooth and soft. The shower felt like a sprinkle, but what can you do???? The room was clean and nice, otherwise. We didn't eat at the buffet, but we did try Ah Sin (just okay) Mon Ami Gabi (very nice) and the pastries place for breakfast was wonderful. Also, our friends had the concierge room added to their plan so I tried that once or twice. I think it is worth the upgrade. You can easily get your $40 worth if you at 2 people and have breakfast their and take advantage of the free drinks (incl. alcohol.) BTW: I didn't gamble here. Instead we went to Bills, 2 doors down. It has lower minimums and a nice middle-of-the-road crowd. Highly recommend it.I would definitely recommend Paris to stay at and Bills to play at.	
