Oct 10 2009 	Nice but not that nice	I recently visited Las Vegas for a six-day conference and made the Paris LV my home. The hotel is very upscale and operates almost like an amusement park, with the themed stores and restaurants. The Eiffel Tower landmark and the simile of the Arc de Triumph make you feel as if you are visiting Europe.The check in experience was typical Las Vegas on a Friday, meaning it was about 1/2 hour standing in line. Since I was traveling on a group hotel rate, I was not too bothered by the room with two queen beds, nor the &quot;wonderful&quot; view of the Bally's Hotel next door, but as I walked to my room, there were several cigarette butts on the hallway carpet, (that had not been cleaned up until late the next afternoon). The room was generally clean, with the exception of mold clinging to the grout in the shower. The design and size of the room was adequate, (even if they had to stuff two queen size beds into it), however, why do the beds have to be situated so close to the walls that you have to climb over the bed to turn on or off the lights mounted on the wall next to them. In addition, in a city that depends on it's convention business, why can't there be at least one wall plug situated near the desk in the room in order to plug in a computer. And as long as I'm talking about computers, one would think that a $15 per day charge for internet access borders on the obscene.The romantic atmosphere would bring me back the Paris, if I were traveling with my wife, but I would not try it again as a business traveler.	
