Sep 24 2009 	Great stay at the Paris!	My Mom and I stayed at the Paris for 4 days – Sept. 13th to 17th. This was our first time in Las Vegas.First, the Paris: We arrived at the Paris at 3:45pm and waited in the check in line for 20 minutes. Farida, who checked us in, was EXCELLENT! We got the room we requested (Luxury) on a non-smoking floor. Farida was very personable and friendly and the person you want to be greeted by after a long day of traveling. The reason for the long check in line was 1300 conventioners checking in that day. Farida asked if we would be using the mini-bar and said no. We had no problems with any unauthorized charges for the mini-bar on our credit card. Remember: this is not a fridge for your personal use so if you buy any beverage at a store, go to the ice machine on your floor to keep your drinks cold.The Paris was a very clean hotel, from the lobby to our room (#1693), to the restaurants. We don’t gamble so we did not spend any time in the casino. The hotel is located mid-Strip which makes is accessible to many hotels close by (Bellagio is across the street; Ceasar’s Palace just down the road; Flamingo across the street; Planet Hollywood is next door). The monorail is great for traveling to the hotels further afield (such as The Venetian, the Sahara). It runs from Ballys which is connected to the Paris. The cost is $5 for one single trip; $13 for a full day pass; $30 for a 3-day pass (they sometimes have discounts on these prices).We ate at Le Village Buffet on the first night for dinner and the food and variety were excellent. We only ate there once as we do not eat a lot food to get our money’s worth at buffets.We ate twice at Mon Ami Gabi – lunch and dinner. We were lucky to be able to get a table outside on the Strip watching the people and the Bellagio fountains. The food at both sittings was very good.We had breakfast at Le Café each morning as we only have cereal or toast and tea. We had dinner there once and had a bad meal – bad as in they advertised one thing but brought something different. Sent it back and ordered something else but the dinner was spoiled because of that and the waiter’s attitude didn’t help either (he was the only person at the Paris that was rude).Check out was a breeze. We checked our account on the tv each day to ensure there were no charges on the card. You can check out on the tv between 7:00am and 3:00pm (I think I got that right). Attractions:1) Bellagio Fountains: they were great, a must see especially at night. We went to see the botanical gardens at the Bellagio but it was being torn down that day as they were changing from their summer display to the autumn display. 2) Secret Garden &amp; Dolphin Encounter (The Mirage) – the Secret Garden holds lions, white tigers, a black panther, and a 10 month old leopard. The Dolphin Encounter does not provide a dolphin performance – it’s a research and training facility and you can watch the trainers with the dolphins.3) The Venetian Hotel: you must go and see the lobby and look at their ceiling – magnificent! We took the gondola ride ($16 per person for about 15 minutes) and enjoyed the experience. We had dinner one night at Canelletos – excellent food. We ate outside (actually inside but it looks like you are eating outside with the ceiling painted as the sky as you will see in some of the hotels) and we were entertained by singers.Shows: We went to the Terry Fator and his Cast of Thousands show at The Mirage. What a laugh! He and his puppets were hilarious. A must see!The only bad experience in Las Vegas was the people standing on the street flicking cards constantly and trying to give them to you as you walk by them – these cards are promoting girls and sex. I’ve been told (whether true or not) that the city can’t get rid of them as they have claimed “restraint of trade”. The cards are thrown on the ground and left there dirtying the street. I say make them pick them up.There were many other hotels and attractions that we wanted to see but we couldn’t fit them into our 4-day stay. I guess we’re going back to Las Vegas next year.	
