Jul 15 2009 	Great hotel for my first time in Vegas	There was just a short line when we checked in at around 6:00 on a Thursday evening. The front desk receptionist was very friendly. We had booked a basic room through an online deal I had found. Total for three nights was just over $200. Asked about possibly being upgraded to a room with a view and was offered the $65 per night upgrade package. We declined since that would have cost about the same as what we paid for the room in the first place. At the end of the check-in process the receptionist said that she had given us an upgraded room anyways. We were in room 2895, which is a Red Room. While there was no view of the Eiffel Tower or the strip from our room, we were able to see some mountains in the distance. The room was great. The décor was modern – large flat screen tv, a sitting area with a sofa, comfortable bed, large bathroom with a separate shower and large tub. There were two small closet areas on either side of the dresser/tv area. There was enough room to put a large suitcase and to hang up some clothes in each of the closets. There was a fridge, but it was for the hotel mini-bar, not personal use. The toiletries provided were of nice quality and included shampoo, conditioner, body soap, lotion, mouthwash, cotton balls, and a shower cap. The room was cleaned promptly everyday. The maids not only made the bed and changed the towels, but also straightened up, arranged the toiletries, etc. We never had to wait for a taxi at the hotel taxi stand. In addition, we used the free hotel shuttle to take us to the Rio one evening. The shuttle stops right outside the hotel down from the taxi and valet stand. This was a very convenient service. Overall we found the service throughout the hotel to be very friendly. The hotel itself was awesome. I couldn’t have asked for a better location for my first trip to Vegas. The Parisian street scene was nice. There were a couple of stores/vendors in the hotel where you could buy small snacks, pop, water, etc. The price was reasonable given the convenience – about $3 for a Gatorade. The casino area was nice and never too crowded. We ate several times at the hotel – twice at the Mon Ami Gabi (once for dinner, and once for breakfast), dinner at Burger Brasserie, and a late night snack at La Creperie. We had intended on having the champagne brunch at Le Village Buffet, but the line was never ending. In fact, there was almost always a line at Le Village Buffet when we passed by – so my suggestion is to go early if you want to try it!Overall, we were very happy with our stay at the Paris Las Vegas and are looking forward to returning for a future visit!!	
