Jun 10 2009 	Liked our stay - 5/24-5/30	We stayed at Paris Sunday, May 24 - Saturday, May 30, 2009. A little background. This is our 3rd stay at Paris. Last one was for one night last September and another trip a few years ago. We typically stay at Bally's. There were 3 of us: me (mid 40's), husband (50) and daughter (mid 20's).Check-in took about 25 minutes or so. We got in line right before noon when several people were checking out. Clerk was friendly, got checked-in and off to our room.If you aren't familiar with Paris, there are 2 or 3 different banks of elevators that go to various floors. Each bank has about 8 elevators. We never had to wait long to go up or down on the elevator.We were in room 437. It was a little over 1/2 way down the hallway. View was of a roof and looked toward the Paris balloon. A view would have been nice but I didn't want to complain about the view because most of our nights were comped. The thing that was not so great was that the service room was right across from our room. The service room was where housekeeping got towels, blankets, pillows, etc. So there was quite a bit of noise and chatter going on every morning.The room has 2 beds, a desk with chair, 2 cushy chairs, a cushy footstool, a small glass table, night stand between the beds, lamps on each side of the bed, a lamp on the desk, and a stand up lamp. There is an armoire that has a closet on each side of the tv area and below the tv are 4 dresser drawers. There was a small refrigerator in the room that I think was stocked and we didn't touch because we didn't want a charge. There is no closet and no luggage stand. There is an ironing board and iron. The bathroom has a blow dryer, magnifying mirror that pulls out from the wall, and large vanity with 1 sink. The glass shower with glass door is separate from the tub. The room is a bit smaller than I remember. No problems with our room being cleanly. The one day I accidentally left the Do Not Disturb sign on the doorknob, they called and left a message to explain why they didn't clean. I called and they came up later when we were ready for them. When we first arrived we needed called for extra blankets and towels. They were delivered within a matter of minutes.The pool is on the 3rd floor so that was a bonus of being on the 4th floor. Take the elevator to 3rd, walk a very short distance, and you are at the pool. The pool was busy on Sunday and Monday due to the holiday weekend but was less busy as the week went on. There was a DJ on Sunday but music only the rest of the time we were there. Saw the cocktail waitress a few times. Never had trouble finding a lounge chair. We tried to go to the pool in the early afternoon most days but a couple of days we went later (around 3:30). By that time the sun has definitely shifted and you have to be strategic in finding a lounger or place in the pool that is in the sun.We didn't gamble a lot in Paris, just not enough time. I went to the casino one morning while waiting on husband and daughter. Found a blazing 7 penny machine. After playing it for about 30-45 minutes, I hit the jackpot! Needless to say I was very happy.We did not eat at Paris. We did eat at Ballys Sidewalk Cafe. Disappointed to find out it is now only open 6am-2pm. The RIO shuttle picks up outside the door (side toward Planet Hollywood). It's free but we tipped $1 for each of us. Monorail station is located on the lower level of Bally's, back near the pool. We like staying near the center of the strip so Paris was perfect for us. We had to catch our plane at 11:00 so checked out around 8:00 a.m. Only waited in line about 2 minutes. Check-out clerk was not a friendly person at all. We wanted to apply any comps to our room charge. Husband had already packed his Total Rewards players card away and she said they couldn't look it up. Grouchiest person I encountered during our entire trip.	
