May 22 2009 	Best Hotel on the Strip	By far the best hotel we have stayed at on the strip so far. We have stayed at NY/NY, MGM, Luxor and Monte Carlo. Our check in experience was a great experience. We booked through expedia at a basic room rate, but when we arrived i showed them a military ID and we were upgraded to the next higher room! The room itself was roomy and inviting. The bathroom was large and exceptionally clean. It had a bathtub and a separate walk in shower. The casino was clean and the drinks were flowing unlike some of the other larger casinos. Paris is attached to the Bally's casino so you don't have to go outside to walk a good ways, north, down the strip. Planet Hollywood is next door with numerous shops and cheaper eating places. We ate every morning at &quot;Mon Ami Gabi&quot; which has an extraordinary eurpean style breakfast with a al fresco dining area right on the strip, with a great view of the bellagio hotel water display.The rooms have a stocked refrigerator, cable TV and adequate heating and air. We also never ran out of hot water (in the shower or bath) which is something that we have had a problem with consistently at MGM and Luxor. We booked this hotel at around $105 per night. Exceptional pool, lockers are a problem (not enough of them), and there are no resturaunts (fast or otherwise) in this hotel open very late at night.	
May 22 2009 	I love it here	I've stayed at this hotel before, and was not disappointed this time.First, the location is very central on the Strip. It is across from Bellagio, between Bally's and Planet Hollywood. There is a monorail station at the adjoining Bally's hotel. You decide if this is a convenient way for you to get around, but the fact is that there is a station in easy striking distance.The &quot;basic&quot; room and bathroom are spacious and very clean. Two small closets flank the TV set (NOT flat panel) in an armoir-like case. There are three drawers in the unit, and more drawers in the nightstand -- enough room to stash a fair amount of stuff. Two comfy armchairs, a table, and an ottoman outfit the room. There is a mini-bar, but one of those with spring-loaded bottles and cans that incur a charge when jostled. Still, we could manage to find space for the odd piece of pizza or fruit, but not much. There is also an ironing board and iron. Lots of nice toiletries in the bathroom -- shampoo, conditioner, lotion, bath gel. The bathroom has a separate tub and shower.Room 630 looks out the back, but we got a good rate and were on the go, so that was okay. The pricier rooms look out over the fountains of Bellagio and the Strip -- nice if you need a special view.The pool here is really nice. First, you are in the shadow of the Eiffel Tower -- such goofy fun. It did not feel at all crowded. There are more than enough chaise lounges for everyone, and the staff do not over-crowd the chairs, i.e. some are kept in reserve and put out when it looks like things might get a little crowded. This made the area seem very nice and spacisous, compared to the crowded pool areas at other hotels. For those who don't want full sun, there are potted trees around, and some parts of the pool area are shaded by the hotel itself at different times of day. There are also private cabanas for rent. A poolside cafe can supply food and drinks at your chair, or you can have lunch under a scrim-rook (I wish it was more shaded -- too much hot sun gets in.)We really like the lobby amenities here. The casino decor has all of the kitschy cliches of Paris -- more goofy fun. There is a really nice range of restaurants from quite expensive fine dining (Eiffel Tower) to moderate places. Mon Ami Gabi, Ah Sin (Asian,) the Cafe, and a steak place all have atmospheric setting, even if off the casino area. Back down a hall are a casual ITalian place; a crepe stand; the buffet; and a breakfast/lunch spot.The find: go to the Lenotre cafe that is very near the elevator bank and newsstand. The morning coffee is slightly less costly than the other breakfast spot and better, and Lenotre also has wonderful pastries and muffins. Also: I don't think people see the very good sandwiches and salads in the case here. You can eat at tables, or grab these items for a quick lunch on the go or when you need to get work done in the room. There are also good ice creams.There are a number of good shops to poke around in.Gustav's bar is a good place to park yourself with a glass of champagne to view casino action, and there are other good spots for drinks throughout the lobby.Service was uniformly nice and friendly throughout the hotel, whether at the check-in desk or business center or pool or on the casino floor.Downsides: internet access in the room is $15 a day -- very annoying in this day. Also: the pool has no charge, but the fitness facility will cost $25. I didn't want to use it, but this always feels like nickle-and-diming.Managed downside: There was one day when a DJ appeared in later afternoon, cranked up some music, and gave away free items, but the next day it seemed like someone (thankfully) asked that the noise level be turned down. So far, Paris has NOT adopted that tacky promotion of fencing off a &quot;European&quot; sun area (read: topless sunbathing, often for a surcharge of the priviliege of being in that area, and/or ogling.) I hope it never does -- that would spoil the nice setting.To sum: while we still might check out other hotels on future stays, there is a strong preference to stay here. It is definitely a place to check.	
May 21 2009 	don't waste your money on a "red room"	Just returned from Paris Las vegas. We booked a &quot;red room&quot; as they were supposed to be more elegant and renovated. The only thing I saw that made it different than the traditional luxury room, was red paint in the bathroom and some kind of red bed boards behind the bed. I think Paris needs to make it what it should be and that is an elegant, classy hotel and a step above a Harrah's property.Also, watch your bill at checkout. We had a charge on our bill for a movie,( which we did not rent) and also three charges for the mini bar (which we did not open). I called the front desk and they told me that there was no way this could happen unless we used those services from the room. The front desk person was not nice about it either. After thinking it over I checked and saw that the charges were made at 1:00 p.m. the day of check in, the only problem there was we did not get our keys until after 4:00 p.m., so that shut them up, and the charges were removed. That was also something we had not seen before. You are not allowed to check in until after 4:00 p.m. as they are all booked, but you can store your luggage for a fee and play table and slot games and spend money until you can use your room to freshen up. Things are changing on the Harrah properties. Maybe check into some of the other hotels, such as Mirage, or Treasure Island, Wynn or Venetian.	
