May 14 2009 	Disappointed over all...	My wife and I paid our first visit to Vegas in late April and we stayed at the Paris.On the good side; it's a terrific location. You can't ask for more. Architecturally, the building is outstanding. The shops in the mall between the hotel and Ballys are quite good. You can find breakfast for 8.95 which includes ham and egg croissant and coffee. That's good value. We enjoyed a fantastic dinner at Mon Ami Gabi, the restaurant that includes the outdoor patio on the strip. One of our travelling companions has eaten there several times and his recommendation did not fail us. If you want to check out the dueling pianos in the lounge you will be entertained; but better be drinking or the bartenders will enforce a two drink minimum. On the downside: the smoky public areas were nauseating. I can't tolerate smoke much and don't have to, thanks to legislation that bans it most places. But compared to other hotels, the Paris's ventilation system does a poor job of clearing the air. I wouldn't spend any time in the casino for that reason.As for service, it was less than cheery at the front desk. But possibly, in character with Paris...Our room, the basic variety was just that: very basic. Not refurbished in a while, nothing to cheer about. But it did have decent mattresses and a working safe, which are both pluses in my book (and I travel a fair amount).All in all, however, this experience wasn't up to what my wife and I had expected.The Paris is a nice place to visit, but next time we'll stay somewhere else.	
