May 11 2009 	Non-smokers people who like clean rooms would be happier elsewhere...	I know it's Las Vegas, I know casinos have been smoky places since the dawn of time... but... this was pretty disgusting. Stayed on a non-smoking floor, but it didn't really help. One of the smokiest bar areas on the casino floor is right next to the main bank of elevators - you have to walk by it to get anywhere. Our room had a thick layer of dust/dirt on the carpet all around the perimeter of the room (you could see it very clearly as the carpet was blue). I guess the maids haven't heard of that crevice/corner attachment. Based on prices alone, you'd think Paris was right up there with Bellagio, Venetian, etc, but we visited those places during our stay and those properties were much more nicely maintained, and the air quality was MUCH better. (People smoke plenty in those hotels but they must work hard to filter/ventilate, because you hardly notice it. When you walk into the Paris, your throat starts to tighten on that first inhale. It's very disturbing.)On the bright side, the location can't be beat (center of the strip, across from the Bellagio and next to Planet Hollywood and great shopping), and we had a nice time around the pool (good music, friendly waitresses). However, unless Paris upgrades their air filtration, or Vegas laws crack down on smoking in casinos (unlikely), I'd avoid this place, especially at the prices they're asking -- even with the economic downturn.	
