Apr 21 2009 	Crowded Quarters	We have been to Las Vegas numerous times, and for this trip decided to stay at Paris. It is not one of the best in town (though not the worst either).Most people say they love Las Vegas but wouldn't want to live there. I can now say the same about this hotel - Great place to visit and check out on your trip, but not to actually stay at.Why do I say this? Well firstly the actual hotel feels very crowded and cramped. The casino and shopping area are always bustling with 'passers by'. There are no quiet spots to relax in. We found it extremely noisy, cramped and confusing compared to most other casinos. There is no sense of sophitication or elegance that one might associate with all things Parisian. Worst still it permanently feels like it's the evening in there. Not great when it's a bright sunny morning outside. There is absolutely no natural light in the buliding at all. Not even at reception.The cafes and restaurants almost always had long lines, so even getting some breakfast felt like a chore. One night (2am) we decided we wanted a cup of tea. We waited in line for twenty minutes to be seated, only to find the cafe actually half empty. Why on earth we had to queue is anyones guess.??? (By the way - They do NOT know how to make a decent cup of tea either) In the end we resorted to McDonalds for our breakfasts. Where we had less of a wait, better tasting tea, and a much smaller check!The rooms are average for Las Vegas. Probably seem amazing to anyone who's never been there before, but take it from me they are nothing special. The bad design of the building also means 75% of the rooms face either the side of Bally's or Plant Hollywood. The adjoining hotels. If you want a strip view it will cost you $65 extra a night. Not worth it in my opinion unless you can bag a room higher than floor 15. Otherwise you basically see the pool and Eiffel Tower. Speaking of the pool - again distinctly average. Only one big round pool. Only 3ft deep even at the centre. No umbrellas to shade anyone, so you'd better want to fry in the sun. On the plus side they do have a nice cafe area there. This can only be accessed by guests, so less busy and actually fairly pleasant. If the management had any sense they would utilise this in the evenings too, with pool side dining and music.Lastly I have to say the service overall was not very good. The exception to this was the buffet where we found all our servers very pleasant and accomodating. I can't reccommend this hotel to anyone really. If you want better casino environment opt for Bellagio, Monte Carlo or Venetian. If it's a great pool you want go for Mandalay Bay, Caesars, Pallazzo or Flamingo. If great shopping is your thing opt for Caesars (for Forum Shops) or Wynn, Pallazzo or Treasure island (for Fashion Show mall). If you want a young, slightly more urban feel opt for Planet Hollywood on the Strip, or Palms or Hard Rock off the strip. Can I think of a single overriding reason why you should choose Paris? Sadly no. It's just average in all respects.	
