Apr 13 2009 	Great Location / Dated Rooms	I have stayed at most of the hotels in vegas over the years, as I have visited this town over 100 times. This was my third stay at Paris Hotel &amp; Casino and my least favorite. .  I don't think the rooms have changed since they opened as they are now showing signs of wear, dated decor and old tv's with a poor cable package. The bathrooms are still very nice but the hallways to the rooms on my floor smelled of old carpet with years of trapped chemical odors. { I have asthma so I am very sensitive to overuse of carpet cleaners, chemicals &amp; smoke.} I had one morning that the hot water for the shower was barely luke warm. If you do not plan a lot of time in your room then these are ok but not luxurious.Check in was a breeze here {about 5 minutes} but I always plan my arrival in Vegas a little early, [usually between 12 &amp; 1. I have found from 2-4pm most of the Las Vegas Hotels have pretty long check in lines.The location of this hotel for 1st time visitors is very good, as it is near the center of the strip across from the Bellagio and connected next door to Bally's. I used the Las Vegas Monorail at the back entrance to Bally's to get down to a convention at the MGM each day and this worked out pretty well. It was a pretty good walk from the Monorail to myroom at Paris but it certainly a good option for getting to the other ends of the strip. The pool area at the hotel is ok, but for those wanting a pool scene this would not be on my short list of great vegas pool areas. Try Caesars, Mandalay Bay or even the Flamingo Hotel &amp; Casino if pool time is your top concern. And always make sure to call ahead to see if the pool area is open.  I do like the Casino here more then many in town as the high ceilings make for a little less smoky atmosphere.I have eaten at many of the Paris restaurants.The bar atop the Eiffel tower has some terrific views for a cocktail. Mon Ami Restaurant is it quite good and the atmosphere terrific. I have also eaten at Les Artistes Steakhouse and found the food to be just ok but the room itself quite stunning. In the walkway from Paris to Bally's you can find the less expensive food {bakery, crepes, buffet, etc} along with a spirited bar that had dueling pianists on one night of my stay. I did notice during my stay the buffet line looked ridiculously long each morning when I walked by. All in all Paris is in a good location but the rooms are getting a little tired. If you are going to stay here make sure you get a really good rate. If you need 5 star luxury in your room and would like a smoke free environment check out Palms Place {the high end resort attatched to the Palms Casino. I stayed there about2 weeks after staying at Paris Hotel and could not believe what a different trip I had for not much more money. It was the best hotel stay I have ever had in Vegas. {Note Palms Place is not on the strip but a very short 2 minute cab ride away.}	
Apr 13 2009 	Paris!! Well Done!	Hey everyone! First of all I am a 44 yr. old Vegas traveller with over 25 visits in the past 10 years. I really enjoy this town. This was our first experience at Paris. Here is our review! We booked to go Easter weekend and decided to stay at Paris because it was the only Harrahs property we had not yet tried out. We got two nights comped and paid $57 for Fri. and Sat. night, so the price was right for four nights. We arrived late (about 11:30pm) on Thurs. night of the long weekend. The check in line had about 8 people in it and we waited for about 10 minutes. The young man who helped us was very polite. He told us unfortunately all standard King rooms where gone so we were going to get a free upgrade, but would have to settle for two queens the first night. He offered us a much bigger upgrade to a King suite (1000 sq. ft.) for an extra $85 per night so we said that is just too much for us this time. So, he put us into the queen upgrade. Strangely, I decided that since he treated us so politley I would tip him $20 as a thanks ( I know, you should do this before he assigns the room). He quickly put it in his pocket and as we started to walk away he motioned us back. He said he really appreciated the tip and was going to put us in the nice King suite for free!!!!!!! It was a really nice room. Great space, furnishings, the bedroom had a wet bar in it with an empty fridge for us to use, business desk and armoire with a TV. Even in the suite the TV was only a tube one, but that didn't bother us! We had a granite coffee table with some nice chairs around it and a couch to sit on. It was nice when we had our other two couple friends to entertain. There was a corridor which came to a &quot;T&quot;, one way led past another desk (where we kept our laptop) into a walk-in closet with the in-room safe. The other way led to the beautiful, huge bathroom!! Lots of marble, wonderful big shower and a separate jacuzzi tub, two vanities, mirrors, etc. No T.V. though!! Then of that room was a door leading to the toilet and the second porcelin toilet which was the one to wash your butt on!!..LOL Who would ever use this?? Very funny. The view was nothing special, 11th floor overlooking the roof with a side view of Planet Holleywood. I WILL ALWAYS USE THE $20 TRICK FROM NOW ON!!! What a great room upgrade for four nights for $5 extra per night!!! The casino was fine! We didin't gamble too much here but we could have. Our friends were both at the Rio so we spent some time over on that part of town. We had a ball playing at the Gold Coast. I did play some Keno machines at Paris and did ok, making about $200 profit. We didn't notice too much smoke. It's actually a pretty nice casino. We only ate at Mon Ami Gabi at Paris and it is as advertised...outstanding!!! You can eat there for reasonable prices as well if you want. The couple we went with only paid $60 for their meal, tip included. I had just won a $200 Keno jackpot outside the restaraunt waiting for the others to arrive so I splurged on filet mignon and it cost us $100. The service was great, I made our reservations online a month before we left and noted to them then that I had celiac disease so I would need gluten free food. When we arrived at the restaraunt they had a special menu for me with all gluten free selections on it...nice service!! We had to wait 15 minutes past our reservation time for an outdoor table cause we wanted to see the view of the Bellagio fountains!! It was great!! The pool area is fine, nothing special bet nice. The view of the Eiffel Tower right in front of you is cool. The two hot tubs where kind of secluded from the pool and big...very nice. Maid service was perfect, we needed a couple of foam pillows delivered as I am allergic to feather and we needed a new remote for the TV as ours did not work. They brought both up to the room 10 min. after a quick phone call from me.  All in all it was a great location, room and hotel. Oh ya, we NEVER waited more that 20 or 30 sec. for an elevator either. Same with Valet parking, never waited more than 5 min. for our vehicle. We would stay there again for sure, but we like to try new places so we will see. Loved Paris!!	
