Apr 8 2009 	Great deal but don't expect any frills--	This was my third time in Vegas and while we got a great price on our standard room at the Paris, and I was excited to be &quot;center strip&quot;, if you will, I'm not sure I would stay here again. There were too many minor issues and there are too many other awesome hotels in Vegas! For instance, the Mirage is usually about the same price, it's not much farther up the Strip, and the rooms are FAR superior to those at the Paris.That said--I will start with check-in. We arrived sometime between 4 and 4:30 PM on a Thursday and they only had TWO people working the &quot;regular&quot; guest check-in line, which meant we waited about 20 minutes, a bit much in my opinion. When I stayed at the Mirage we had to approach the front desk numerous times during our stay, for check-in and otherwise, and we never waited more than a minute or two.Also, the Paris casino is something of a maze and very difficult to get around in! Much more so than the ones at Mandalay Bay and the Mirage.Anyway, on to the room--we stayed in a standard room and let me tell you, at the Paris, you get what you pay for. Although the room was nice and big and the bed/sheets/pillows were soft and comfortable, I had the following issues:-There was no comforter on the bed. I like to &quot;sleep cold&quot; (with the A/C on a lower temp) and if I hadn't had someone to cuddle with, it would have been AWFUL.-The carpet was very worn and there were random marks all over the walls.-Even though we didn't watch much TV, the other Vegas hotels I've experienced led me to expect a flatscreen. Not so at the Paris--if you have a standard room, expect a crappy, small, old tube television.-It was annoying to see the usual sign in the bathroom about how the hotel is trying to be &quot;green&quot;, so &quot;hang up your towels&quot; etc. &quot;if you want to re-use them&quot;. Personally, I don't mind using my towels/washcloths for a couple of days and usually hang them up to save water etc. at hotels. But at the Paris this is impossible because there is only one TINY towelbar in the entire bathroom! They really shouldn't have those signs at all, considering.-I brought a travel-sized container of facewash with me that happened to be the same size and shape as the shampoo/conditioner/lotion etc. containers that the hotel provides. They threw out my facewash on me because apparently every day they take all of the slightly used containers out of the shower and toss them! This is both silly and frustrating because I had to go without facewash because of it.Otherwise, I will say that the bathroom was awesome! Very big, with a separate shower and tub. Much nicer than the bathroom in my room at the Mirage, which was tiny.We ate at four of the &quot;restaurants&quot; at the Paris during our stay there. The Lenotre Bakery has great food but crappy coffee. My latte tasted more like water than coffee and my boyfriend's cappuccino wasn't much better. The bakery was also pretty expensive. I ate at Mon Ami Gabi for the second time and was just as impressed as the first time I ate there. Not cheap by any means, but awesome food and service! We had breakfast at Le Cafe on our second morning there and it was just okay. The hollandaise sauce on my Eggs Benedict was questionable, my boyfriend's bagel with eggs and salmon was average, our cappuccinos were the same blah ones that we had at Lenotre, and the service was ridiculously slow. Finally, we had crepes from Le Creperie and while they were tasty--don't expect anything like a REAL French crepe. They were too thick, first of all, and they felt the need to smother my Nutella Crepe with hot chocolate and whipped cream on TOP of the Nutella. A bit much.Check-out at 11 AM on a Sunday was a long process, as is to be expected. The luggage storage service at the Paris was great/easy, though!All in all, while I can't give the Paris an amazing rating, if you can tell that you're getting a good price on the rooms I say go for it.	
