Mar 20 2009 	Great Hotel Great Location	We recently completed a 5 day, 4 night stay at the Paris. This is our upteenth stay in Vegas and decided to try Paris this (looking to compare it to the Monte Carlo). From check-in to departure our stay was better than expected (with one exception). Here is the long version.Check-In: Quick, pleasant and efficient. We waited in line approximately 5 minutes (a 1:30 pm check in on a Monday afternoon). We were given a room on the 22nd floor.Elevators: Located a very short walk from check in. During our stay, we never waited more than 45 seconds for an elevator (and the hotel was heavily booked with convention people). 3 sets of elevators divided by floors.Room: We booked a room with 2 queens. Tastefully decorated with excellent temperature controls. A small television (given today's standards) with a limited number of stations. (who cares, it's Vegas!) The bathroom was a good size with the tub and shower being separate affairs (shower enclosure, very nice). Ice machine was located in one of the other &quot;wings&quot;. Here is my only complaint. Our room (2239) was located directly across the hall from where the housekeeping staff loaded up their carts each morning. Starting at 8:30 am (not all that early, unless it's Vegas) we were serenaded by pounding carts and the United Nations of languages. I would presume that these rooms are located on each floor, so when checking in request to stay away from the &quot;39's&quot;. Restaurants: We only ate at one of the Paris locations . The Burger Brassiere has excellent burgers. Check Out: We used the express check out, so certainly didn't have any complaints about that.Overall Impression: We would certainly stay at this hotel again. Slightly &quot;nicer&quot; than the Monte Carlo (especially with the City Center Construction still going on, finished in 9 months according to the news today). A great location in the middle of the Strip. I would recommend this hotel to almost any traveler.	
Mar 20 2009 	Sign me up again!!!	Top Ten Reasons to stay at the Paris Hotel1. Hotel Staff is kind and courtious2. Rooms - comfy bed and great view3. Village Buffet - excellent food - don't miss the crepes!!4. Pool Side - Lots of space and clean5. Shops - good variety6. Le Renezous Concierge Lounge Packaged - well worth the upgrade7. Location is excellent - A comfortable (sometimes lengthy walk) to the nightlife8. Dueling pianos very entertaining (although drinks are pricey)9. Interior makes you feel like you are actually in Paris!10. Mon ami gabi ......MMMMMMMM!(10.2) did I mention that you shouldn't miss the crepes!!!DONT MISS WALKING DOWN THE BOULEVARD!! Singing restaurants and Le Burger Basserie should not be missed.A few things to be improved....1. No real night life bar for dancing during the week (Risque only open on weekends)2. No $5.00 tables, but it means the cliental is respectful (no frat boys... no offense!!)3. A long line up at check in, but that is to be expected when a hotel is sold out. Staff very quick at storing bags and then bringing them to our room when we got our room!	
Mar 19 2009	Rooms and Location are nice; Staff and policies not so customer friendly	I have stayed at over 25 hotels in Las Vegas and so I like the review to place the hotel in relation to other well-knowns. I would place the Paris about equal with Mirage, TI and NYNY. It's a notch or two above MGM, Luxor, Planet Hollywood &amp; Monte Carlo. It rates lower than Mandalay Bay, Rio &amp; Cesars.On the plus side: The location is great and there are a large variety of restaurants on the property. It is also very clean.On the down side: Like most big vegas hotels. You are a number and they do little to dispell the notion. On my reservation I asked for a smoke free king room (not too exotic right...) I was told when I checked in AT 6 PM! that this type of room was not ready yet. What's up with that? They can't get rooms cleaned by 6PM?? At 8 AM the following morning, I was greeted with &quot;....Housekeeping... Housekeeping!... They also have a 10 am checkout time. So I guess at the Paris, don't count on a hotel room for much more than 12 hours. Talked with the mgr about this, They just really don't care. This must have been the hotel that Bob Seger stayed in when he penned that seminal classic from the '70's &quot; I feel like a Number&quot;	
Mar 19 2009 	Conference Stay February 2009	Overall pleasant experience, but nothing spectacular. Had a king room...514. Furnishings nice for average hotels...but average at best for Las Vegas Strip. Housekeeping did great job cleaning the room all week..but did not restock my fridge once during a 5 day stay. Just as well, as they saved me from buying $4 mini cans of soda nightly. LOL Conference facilities were more than adequate...and not as long a walk from the rooms as at some Strip hotels. Dueling Pianos bar was great entertainment, located right at the corner of the wlakway if you are going to self=parking garage or to conference facilities. Not enough outlets in the room. In order to plug in my phone at laptop at the desk, I was forced to unplug a lamp. Same thing by the bed....NOT ONE extra outlet by the bed.	
Mar 17 2009 	not impressed	My initial impression of the hotel wasn't helped by a slow check-in with an arrogant desk clerk who didn't try to be helpful and just seemed to have a take it or leave it attitude.Our room was nice and the hotel is in an excellent location and we got a rate of $75 a night so the value was good. That being said I would stay here if we could get that rate again but I would not stay here and pay their typical rate. We ate at Mon Ami Gabi and had good food but not very good service and my wife was still hungry when we left.We also ate at Les Artistes Steakhouse and had good food and good service but it is pricey for what you get.Le Village Buffet is good for breakfast.	
Mar 17 2009 	Hotel exceeded my expectations whether in Vegas or not!	My wife and I loved the way the hotel and Casino areas were decorated as streetscapes of Paris and other regions of France. The meals were fantastic and compared to other locations on the strip, reasonable. Leave dietary concerns at home though and simply endulge and enjoy. Far more comfortable feel to hotel than what we envisioned by viewing the website. Service for the most part was excellent and being interconnected with Bally's was a bonus as the two Casino's have quite a different feel to them. Right in the heart of the strip and convenient to most other big named locations. Walked both directions on different days to see each and every Casino. That only reconfirmed that we picked the right hotel to stay at to begin with for our tastes. Two things that were sub-par was beverage service while playing at the tables and our room (no upgrade chosen) that faced south-west towards parking garage and airport). Did not care that room did not have a great view but McCarron Airport is quite the busy place and with planes arriving late and taking off early, facing this direction is a major nuisance unless you live close to an airport and have learned to live with this noise. Facing north or east (strip) would have been much preferred and offerred a more restful, longer sleep. This problem would exist though for all hotels in the south end of the strip with many even worse off than Paris! Vegas can be an in your face, overwhelming place, but the Paris L.V. Hotel was an oasis in the middle of what can at times be a very chaotic place. By the way... absolutely loved how the tower was integrated into the design and building of the Casino area!	
